\chapter{Methodology}

\section{Normalization}
Min-max normalization is used in the proposed system.Min-Max normalization transforms value from X to Y in range [A, B] i.e [0,1].
The determination takes place by using formula mentioned below in eqn ${(1)}$.\\

$Y=\frac{\left(X-minimum \thinspace \thinspace value\thinspace  of\thinspace X\right)}{\left(maximum\thinspace \thinspace value \thinspace  of\thinspace X-minimum \thinspace value \thinspace of \thinspace X\right)}\times\left(B-A\right)+A $ $\thinspace \thinspace \thinspace   $   $......{(1)}$

\section{MCA}

MCA approach is developed based on triangle area map technique, which is used to present the correlations within network traffic data.
These correlations are extracted from the statistical properties (e.g.the number of data bytes from source to destination,
number of wrong fragments and the number of connections to the same host as the current connection in the past two seconds etc.)
of the network traffic.The traffic of denial of service attack behaves differently from the legitimate network traffic and network traffic behavior
is reflected through statistical properties. To well describe statistical properties, multivariate correlation analysis (MCA) information is used.
The MCA employs the triangle area method to extract the geometrical correlation among features within traffic record.
In MCA triangle area technique is used to extract the multivariate correlations.\\

Given kddcup99 dataset $ X=\left\{x_{1} ,x_{2},....,x_{n}\right\}$ , where $ x_{i}=\left[ f_1^i \thinspace \thinspace  f_2^i .......f_m^i \right],\left( 1\leq i \leq n\right) $
represents the $ i^{th} $ m-dimentional traffic record. we apply triangular area method to extract the geometrical correlation between the $j^{th}$ and $ k^{th} $ features
in the vector $x_{i}$ .\\

The triangle area{(TA)} is calculated by using formula which consists of $ j^{th}$ and $ k^{th}$ feature:\\

 $TA_{j,k}^{i}=\frac{\left(\mid f_j^i\mid\times \mid f_k^i\mid\right)  }{2}....{(2)}$\\

 where $ 1\leq i \leq n, \thinspace 1\leq j \leq m,\thinspace 1\leq k \leq m $ , and $ j\neq k $.To make complete analysis , all possible permutations
 of any two distinct features in the vector $x_{i}$ are extracted and corresponding triangle areas are determined.
 A TAM is constructed and all the triangle areas are arranged in map with respect to their indexes.For example,the $ TA_{j,k}^{i} $ is positioned on the
 $j^{th}$ row and $k^{th}$ column of the map $ TAM^i$ , which has a size of $ m\times m $ .The values of the elements on the diagonal of
 the map are set to zeros $ \left( Tr_{j,k}^i = 0 ,if j=k \right)$ because we only care about the correlation between each pair of
 distinct features.For the nondiagonal elements $ TA_{j,k}^{i} $ and $TA_{k,j}^{i} $  where $ j\neq k $ , they represents the areas
 of the same triangle.This infers that the values of $ TA_{j,k}^{i} $ and $TA_{k,j}^{i} $ are actually equal.Hence the $ TAM^i $\
 is symmetric matrix having elements of zero on the main diagonal.\\

when comparing two TAMs, we can imagine them as two images symmetric along their main diagonals.Any differences ,identified on the upper triangles
of the images, can be found on their lower triangles as well.Therefore, to perform a quick comparison of the two TAMs, we can choose either
the upper triangles or lower traingles of the TAMs only.we considered the lower triangles of the TAMs in the remaining computation.
 Then lower triangles of the $ TAM^i $ is converted into new correlation vector is denoted in equation ${(3)}$ .\\

$TAM_{lower}^{i}=\left[TA_{2,1}^{i} \thinspace \thinspace TA_{3,1}^{i}.....TA_{m,1}^{i}\thinspace \thinspace TA_{3,2}^{i} \thinspace \thinspace \thinspace \thinspace TA_{4,2}^{i} .....TA_{m,2}^{i} ..... TA_{m,m-1}^{i}\right]....(3) $ \\




$\overline{{TAM_{lower}^i}}=\frac{1}{x}\times\sum_{i=1}^x {TAM_{lower}^i}$.....{(4)}\\


After lower triangular matrix is determined then covariance matrix is calculated using mathematical equation {(5)}.Then Mahalnobis distance is determined
using the equation {(7)}.All other mathematical concepts related to covariance matrix is used from[2].\\
%\begin{align}

 %TAMlower=\sum_{i=1}^{x} TAM^i_{lower} {TAMlower}


 \[
 { covariance}=     \begin{bmatrix}
     \sigma\left(TA_{2,1}\thinspace , \thinspace TA_{2,1}\right)& \cdots & \sigma\left(TA_{2,1}\thinspace , \thinspace TA_{n,n-1}\right) \\
   %     \vdots &                            \ddots                                    & \vdots \\

     \sigma\left(TA_{3,1}\thinspace , \thinspace TA_{2,1}\right)& \cdots & \sigma\left(TA_{3,1}\thinspace , \thinspace TA_{n,n-1}\right) \\

      \vdots &                            \ddots                                    & \vdots \\

     \sigma\left(TA_{n,n-1}\thinspace , \thinspace TA_{2,1}\right) & \cdots & \sigma\left(TA_{n,n-1}\thinspace , \thinspace TA_{n,n-1}\right)
     \end{bmatrix}{ .....{(5)}}
 \]
\\

The covariance between two arbitrary elements in the lower triangle of TAM is defined below in equation {(6)}\\

$ \sigma\left( Tr_{j,k}\thinspace , Tr_{l,v} \right)=\frac{1}{x-1}\sum_{i=1}^x \thinspace \left( Tr_{j,k}^i -\mu Tr_{j,k}\right) \times \left( Tr_{l,v}^i -\mu Tr_{l,v}\right) $ ......{(6)}\\
\\
$ \mu Tr_{j,k} \thinspace \thinspace and \thinspace \thinspace \mu Tr_{l,v} $ is the mean of the $ \left(j,k\right)^{th} $ elements and  the $ \left(j,k\right)^{th} $ elements of the TAMs over
x traffic records respectively.\\

$MD^{i}=\sqrt{\frac{\left(TAM_{lower}^i-\overline{TAM_{lower}^i}\right)T \thinspace \times \thinspace TAM_{lower}^i-\overline{TAM_{lower}^i}}{covariance}}$  .....{(7)}
%\end{align}


\section{SVM}
The support vector machine is used for the classification of traffic. The support vector machine separates data points into two classes. By using SVM technique Attack or normal traffic is determined. It consists of separating hyperplane which is used to separate data. The points nearest to separating hyperplane are called as support vectors. In this need to maximize the distance between the separating hyperplane and Support Vectors. The figure 7.1 shows SVM overview.
Support vector machine is first suggested by vapnik for classification[29].

\begin{figure}[h!]
\centering
 %Requires \usepackage{graphicx}
\includegraphics[width=0.6\textwidth]{svm}\\
\caption{ SVM overview }
\end{figure}
\newpage

\subsection{SMO}

Sequential minimal optimization (SMO) is an algorithm for solving the quadratic programming (QP) problem that arises during the training of support vector machines. It was invented by John Platt in 1998 at Microsoft Research. SMO is widely used for training support vector machines and is implemented by the popular LIBSVM tool. The publication of the SMO algorithm in 1998 has generated a lot of excitement in the SVM community, as previously available methods for SVM training were much more complex.\\

\begin{figure}[h!]
\centering
 %Requires \usepackage{graphicx}
\includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{smo}\\
\caption{ SMO overview }
\end{figure}

In above figure, The horizontal thin line at every step represents the training set, while the thick boxes represent the Lagrange multipliers being optimized at that step.
A given group of three lines corresponds to three training iterations, with the first iteration at the top.\\


Unlike previous SVM learning algorithms, which use numerical quadratic programming (QP) as an inner loop, SMO uses an analytic QP step. Because SMO spends most of its time evaluating the decision function, rather than performing QP, it can exploit data sets which contain a substantial number of zero elements. Here, these data sets are called sparse. SMO does particularly well for sparse data sets, with either binary or non-binary input data[30].\\
\\
SMO chooses to solve the smallest possible optimization problem at every step. For the standard SVM QP problem, the smallest possible optimization problem involves two Lagrange multipliers because the Lagrange multipliers must obey a linear equality constraint. At every step, SMO chooses two Lagrange multipliers to jointly optimize, finds the optimal values for these multipliers, and updates the SVM to reflect the new optimal values[30].\\




The algorithm proceeds as follows:
\begin{enumerate}
\item 	Find a Lagrange multiplier $\alpha{1}$  that violates the Karush–Kuhn–Tucker (KKT) conditions for the optimization problem.
\item Pick a second multiplier $\alpha{2}$   and optimize the pair $\left(\alpha{1},\alpha{2}\right)$ .
\item Repeat steps 1 and 2 until convergence.
\end{enumerate}

When all the Lagrange multipliers satisfy the KKT conditions (within a user-defined tolerance), the problem has been solved. Although this algorithm is guaranteed to converge, heuristics are used to choose the pair of multipliers so as to accelerate the rate of convergence. This is critical for large data sets since there are $ n\times\left(n-1\right)$ possible choices for  $\alpha{i}$ and $\alpha{j}$.

